> ~x.indexOf(…) would be “starts with” rather than “contains”, for negative numbers such as -2 (from ~1) are truthy.<p>Nope, here&#x27;s an example you can run it run in your console:<p><pre><code>    function contains(needle, haystack) {
      return Boolean(~haystack.indexOf(needle));
    }

    var haystack = &quot;The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog&quot;;
    console.log(contains(&quot;The&quot;, haystack));
    console.log(contains(&quot;dog&quot;, haystack));
    console.log(contains(&quot;brown fox jumps&quot;, haystack));
</code></pre>
Here are three potential cases:<p><pre><code>    haystack.indexOf(&#x27;dog&#x27;) = 40 -> truthy
    ~40 = -41 -> truthy

    haystack.indexOf(&#x27;The&#x27;) = 0 -> falsey (WRONG)
    ~0 = -1 -> truthy (FIXED)

    haystack.indexOf(&#x27;nope&#x27;) = -1 -> truthy (WRONG)
    ~-1 = 0 -> falsey (FIXED)</code></pre>
